## Purpose & principles

- **Audience**: Developers (maintainers, contributors, API consumers). Assume technical literacy; avoid unnecessary hand-holding.
- **Goal**: Answer “what is this?”, “how do I run it?”, and “where do I go next?” in under two minutes.
- **Tone**: Direct, scannable, and factual. Prefer bullets and short paragraphs over long prose.
- **Length**: Prefer brevity. Link to detailed docs instead of duplicating them in the README.

---

## Structure & headers

Use a consistent hierarchy so humans and tools can parse the doc:

- **Single `#`**: Document title only (e.g. `# Project Name`).
- **`##`**: Major sections (Overview, Installation, Usage, API, Contributing).
- **`###`**: Subsections within those. Avoid going deeper than `###` for normal READMEs.

Example outline:

```markdown
# My Service

## Overview
## Requirements
## Installation
## Usage
## Configuration
## API Reference
## Contributing
## License
```

Keep section names predictable. Common patterns: [Overview](https://www.writethedocs.org/guide/writing/beginners-guide-to-docs/), [Getting started](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-readmes), Installation, Usage, API/Reference, Contributing, License.

